                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                              
	Mumbai, Oct. 18 (PTI): Indian-born Canadian writer Rohinton Mistry today voiced dismay over Mumbai University dropping his Booker-nominated book Such A Long Journey from its syllabus following a Shiv Sena demand, terming the varsitys quick action as deluxe service via express delivery.          
	A political party demanded change in syllabus and Mumbai University provided deluxe service via express delivery making the book disappear the very next day, Mistry said in an email, copies of which were distributed by social activist Anand Patwardhan.                  
	Srinagar (PTI): Hardline Hurriyat leader Masrat Alam, seen as the spearhead of street protests in Kashmir Valley, for the past four months, was arrested on Monday night. Alam, the Muslim League chief who has been underground since June, was apprehended in Tailbal on the outskirts of Srinagar and was booked under the Public Safety Act, officials said. He has been taken away to an undisclosed destination for questioning.                  
	Kanpur (PTI): A retired air force officer allegedly committed suicide on Sunday by hanging himself from the ceiling of his house, police said. Ramshankar, 74, was living alone and suffering from some illness. A suicide note found in his home attributed the cause to his illness and loneliness.                  
	 Jammu (PTI): Three girls allegedly abandoned by their father were rescued by a sweeper at Jammu railway station on Monday, police said. The sisters were abandoned after their mother, who had an illicit affair, fled home last week.
                                                                                                                                              
